# Authoring protocols (maintainers only)

This repo *ships* rules, skills, hooks, and agents. Picking the wrong one is the
main way this plugin breaks. This rule governs editing this repository; it is
not shipped to users.

## Pick by mechanism, not by topic

| | Loaded | Use it for |
|---|---|---|
| **Rule** (`rules/*.mdc`, `alwaysApply: true`) | Every turn, in the system prompt | Invariants and style that must hold no matter what the model is doing |
| **Skill** (`skills/*/SKILL.md`) | When the model matches the `description` | A procedure with steps, decisions, and tool calls |
| **Reference** (`skills/*/references/*.md`) | When its own skill says to read it | Detail too long for the skill body |
| **Hook** (`hooks/*.py`) | On a Cursor lifecycle event | Deterministic work that must not depend on the model deciding to do it |
| **Agent** (`agents/*.md`) | When a skill delegates | Noisy or expensive work that should stay out of the main context |

Two questions settle almost every case:

1. *Does it change how the model behaves even when no workflow is running?* →
   Rule. Otherwise Skill.
2. *Would it be wrong for the model to skip this?* → Hook, not prose.

## Rules

- **One always-on rule.** `rules/learning-tutor.mdc` is it. A second always-on
  rule means two things claim to be the baseline, and they will drift apart.
- Keep it under ~90 lines. Always-on text is paid for on every single turn.
- Do not put procedures in rules. A numbered workflow with CLI calls is a skill.
- Do not use `alwaysApply: false` rules for policy that a skill depends on.
  Description-matched rules load *probabilistically*: a skill that says "persist
  through the recording policy" is a skill that silently does nothing when that
  rule does not load. This is the exact failure this architecture was rebuilt to
  remove — do not reintroduce it.

## Skills

- **Self-contained.** Every skill carries the literal commands it needs. Never
  delegate a step to another rule or skill by name and assume it loaded.
  Duplication across skills is correct here; DRY across context boundaries is a
  bug, not a virtue.
- **Disjoint descriptions.** The description is the routing table. Two skills
  whose descriptions match the same request is the classic failure mode — the
  model picks arbitrarily. Every description states both *when to use* and
  *when not to* ("Not for …"), and names the sibling skill that owns the
  excluded case.
- A skill under ~10 lines with no steps and no tool calls is style, not a
  procedure. Fold it into the always-on rule.
- `disable-model-invocation: true` only for skills that must never fire on
  their own (`study-log`).

## Hooks

- Adapters only: read JSON from stdin, call into `runtime/`, write JSON to
  stdout. Domain logic lives in `runtime/learning/`, never in `hooks/`.
- Always fail open (`{"continue": true}`), and log diagnostics to stderr, never
  into the agent's context.
- Line budgets are enforced by `scripts/smoke_install.py`. If an adapter is
  outgrowing its budget, the logic belongs in `runtime/`.

## Enforce policy in code when you can

The CLI already rejects generic topics and base languages, and normalizes
aliases. Deterministic beats persuasive: if a constraint can live in
`runtime/learning/topics.py`, put it there instead of restating it in prose that
the model may or may not be shown.

## Before committing

```bash
python3 scripts/verify_release.py
```

`scripts/check_architecture.py` enforces the structural invariants above —
single always-on rule, self-contained skills, disjoint triggers, one writer for
`covered`. Fix the architecture rather than relaxing the check.
